20
# =============================================================================
# .nvmrc — Node Version Manager Runtime Configuration
# =============================================================================
#
# Purpose:
#   Declares the Node.js version that this project targets. NVM (Node Version
#   Manager) reads this file when you run `nvm use` or `nvm install` from this
#   directory, automatically switching your shell to the specified version.
#   This ensures every developer (and CI/CD pipeline) builds and runs the
#   project with the same major version of Node, avoiding subtle bugs caused
#   by runtime differences.
#
#   Tools that honour .nvmrc automatically:
#     - nvm (nvm use / nvm install)
#     - fnm (fast Node manager)
#     - nodenv (via nodenv-nvmrc plugin)
#     - avn (automatic version switching)
#     - Many CI platforms (Netlify, Vercel, Render, etc.)
#     - Docker build scripts (common convention)
#
# Value: 20
#   This pins the project to Node.js 20.x (Iron LTS). Node 20 was promoted to
#   LTS on 2023-10-24 and will receive security updates until 2026-04-30.
#   Using a bare major version (20 rather than 20.x or 20.18.0) lets nvm
#   resolve the latest available 20.x release, balancing stability with the
#   convenience of picking up patch-level fixes automatically.
#
#   Acceptable alternative values (if upgrading later):
#     - "22"          → Current LTS (active until 2027-04-30)
#     - "lts/*"       → Latest LTS release (alias managed by nvm)
#     - "lts/iron"    → Explicitly the Iron LTS codename
#     - "20.18.0"     → A specific patch version (CI hermetic builds)
#     - "node"        → Latest stable release (avoid — too loose for teams)
#
# Related files:
#   - package.json  → engines.node field should match or constrain this version
#   - .node-version → alternative file read by fnm/nodenv (this project uses
#                      .nvmrc instead; having both can cause conflicts)

